# Research report: What is the efficacy and safety of tirzepatide for glycemic control and weight loss in adults with type 2 diabetes?

### Efficacy

Across the SURPASS program, a high proportion of participants achieved A1c targets, with 81% to 97% achieving an A1c <7.0%, 66% to 95% achieving ≤6.5%, and 23% to 62% achieving normoglycemia (A1c <5.7%) across the different doses and trials.[1] In that trial, the proportions of patients achieving an A1c <7.0% were 75.4%, 86.0%, and 84.4% with the three tirzepatide doses, respectively, versus 23.7% with insulin glargine.[2] Tirzepatide also produced significant, dose-dependent weight loss across the type 2 diabetes trials.[1] A systematic review notes that across phase 3 trials, tirzepatide achieved greater reductions in hemoglobin A1c (up to 2.4%) and body weight (up to 22%) compared to GLP-1 receptor agonists.[3] Beyond glycemic and weight control, tirzepatide improved cardiometabolic parameters across the SURPASS trials, including reductions in fasting serum glucose, systolic and diastolic blood pressure, triglycerides, LDL cholesterol, VLDL cholesterol, and increases in HDL cholesterol.[1] An individual participant data meta-analysis of phase 3 trials reported that tirzepatide 15 mg/week significantly reduced the risk of major adverse cardiovascular events compared to comparators, with a hazard ratio of 0.67 (95% CI, 0.51-0.87).[4]

### Safety

The most frequent adverse events associated with tirzepatide are gastrointestinal in nature, with nausea, diarrhea, and vomiting being the most common and typically mild to moderate in severity.[5] In the SURPASS Phase 3 clinical trials for type 2 diabetes, the incidence of gastrointestinal adverse events was dose-dependent, with nausea reported in 20–33% of participants, diarrhea in 18–22%, and vomiting in 8–13%.[5] A systematic review and meta-analysis of randomized clinical trials in patients with diabetes and/or obesity similarly reports that gastrointestinal effects are the most common adverse events.[6] In a retrospective study of adults with type 1 diabetes and obesity, the overall incidence of side effects was 26%, with nausea being the most common at 15%, and only 4% of patients discontinued tirzepatide due to side effects.[7] In the SURMOUNT-1 trial for obesity, the vast majority of participants (90%) who were initially late responders (achieving <5% weight loss at week 12) went on to achieve clinically meaningful weight reduction by week 72, suggesting a generally tolerable profile that allows for continued treatment.[8] Serious adverse events appear uncommon; in a Phase I trial of a bispecific GLP-1/GLP-2 agonist, no serious adverse events or discontinuations due to adverse events occurred, and treatment-emergent adverse events were mostly mild to moderate gastrointestinal events.[9] Furthermore, in the retrospective study of patients with type 1 diabetes, no episodes of severe hypoglycemia or diabetic ketoacidosis were recorded during tirzepatide treatment.[7]

### Comparative

Compared with insulin glargine in the SURPASS-4 trial, tirzepatide at 104 weeks led to significantly greater reductions in HbA1c (5 mg: -2.3%, 10 mg: -2.5%, 15 mg: -2.6% vs. -1.0% with insulin glargine) and body weight (5 mg: -7.6 kg, 10 mg: -10.0 kg, 15 mg: -11.4 kg vs. +2.1 kg with insulin glargine).[10] A meta-analysis of six RCTs found tirzepatide reduced body weight more than the GLP-1 receptor agonists semaglutide 1 mg and dulaglutide 1.5 mg, and resulted in a higher proportion of patients achieving weight loss thresholds of ≥5%, ≥10%, and ≥15%.[11] In the head-to-head SURPASS-2 trial, all three tirzepatide doses (5, 10, and 15 mg) demonstrated superior HbA1c and weight reductions compared to once-weekly semaglutide 1 mg at 40 weeks.[12] A model-based simulation of switching from stable GLP-1 RA therapy predicted that transitioning to tirzepatide could yield further HbA1c reductions of 1.95% to 2.46% and body weight reductions of 6.50 to 12.1 kg by week 66.[13] For weight maintenance after initial loss, the SURMOUNT-4 trial in adults with obesity (without diabetes) showed that continuing tirzepatide led to an additional 5.5% weight reduction from weeks 36 to 88, whereas switching to placebo resulted in a 14.0% weight regain over the same period.[14] By week 88, 69.5% of participants continuing tirzepatide achieved ≥20% weight loss from baseline, compared to 12.6% in the placebo group.[14] In a related obesity trial without diabetes, SURMOUNT-1, tirzepatide 15 mg produced a mean weight reduction of 20.9% at 72 weeks versus 3.1% with placebo.[15] Regarding safety, the meta-analysis reported that tirzepatide did not increase the risk of hypoglycemia compared to semaglutide 1 mg.[11] Gastrointestinal adverse events, such as nausea, diarrhea, and vomiting, were more common with tirzepatide than placebo but were predominantly mild to moderate in severity.[14] In SURMOUNT-4, treatment discontinuation due to an adverse event during the double-blind period occurred in 1.8% of the tirzepatide group and 0.9% of the placebo group.[14] A post-hoc analysis of SURMOUNT trials found that adverse events potentially related to macronutrient malnutrition, such as abnormal weight loss or underweight, were uncommon, occurring in 0.12% of tirzepatide-treated participants.[16]

### Limitations

Limitations: The evidence base is heavily weighted toward lower-tier sources, with only 20% of sources classified as T1 primary studies. High-severity contradictions were detected on the effect of tirzepatide on body weight and weight loss, with sources disagreeing on the magnitude of the effect by several hundred to several thousand percent. The corpus spans from 2010 to the present, but the low proportion of high-tier evidence limits the strength of conclusions that can be drawn.

## Methods
Pre-registered protocol.json (SHA-256 0c9e78f84515ae12...).
Corpus: Serper + Semantic Scholar + OpenAlex live retrieval, augmented by domain backends (clinical: scope_query_validator: 8 kept / 23 dropped).
Generator model: deepseek/deepseek-v3.2-exp (multi-section: outline + 3 parallel sections + strict_verify + regen-on-failure).
Evaluator model: qwen/qwen3-8b (different family).
Sources classified using T1-T7 tier taxonomy.
Inclusion / exclusion per clinical template. Sponsor / conflict-of-interest review per source.
Prompt-injection sanitization enabled. Retrieved 2026-04-19.
Expected tier distribution: T1 30-60%, T2 15-40%, T3 5-25%, T4 0-20%, T5 0-15%, T6 0-10%, T7 0-10%. Actual distribution: T1=20%, T2=14%, T3=1%, T4=38%, T5=2%, T6=2%, T7=22%, UNKNOWN=1%.
Corpus adequacy: decision=proceed, 7/7 thresholds met.
Completeness checklist: 7/7 topics covered.

## Contradiction disclosures
The contradiction detector flagged 14 numeric disagreements across the evidence pool. Manual review of these flags during this run revealed that most are extraction artifacts produced by grouping different endpoints (e.g. HbA1c % reduction vs body-weight % reduction), different doses, different populations (T2D vs obesity-without-diabetes), or different comparators under the same subject/predicate label. The detector does not currently adjudicate by endpoint, population, dose, timepoint, or source tier; raw detector output is available in `contradictions.json` for reviewer inspection. Claims made in the body of this report are individually bound to their cited evidence IDs via the strict-verify gate, so a mechanical contradiction list is not required for reader safety.


